  "suggestion": "The beauty dimension is decoupled from evolutionary pressure. Beauty is scored but not sought. Evolution has optimized survival and efficiency to local maxima, but because beautiful organisms don't inherit better chances or attract resources, the beauty score drifts randomly. The plateau isn't a fitness limit—it's a dimensional collapse. You need beauty to *matter to the organisms themselves*, not just to the scorekeeper. Couple aesthetic properties to reproductive success or resource acquisition, and evolution will chase beauty as eagerly as it chases efficiency.; [medium] Make beauty a perceptual property that drives organism behavior. Add sensory cells that detect beauty in other organisms and the environment. Organisms make movement/growth decisions based on proximity to beauty. Create a 'beauty attractant' gradient in the world that organisms follow. — Beauty is currently a scoring metric but evolutionarily inert—organisms don't care if they're beautiful. When beauty becomes something organisms *seek out* and *are drawn to*, it enters the selection pressure loop naturally. Beautiful organisms near beautiful organisms will tend to cluster, reproducing together and creating positive fitness correlations. This couples the beauty dimension to actual survival advantages.; [medium] Add temporal life phases with different growth rules and beauty rewards for each phase. Organisms progress through youth (rapid growth, low beauty weight), maturity (reproduction, medium beauty weight), and senescence (aesthetic transformation/bloom, high beauty weight). Different cell types activate in different phases. — Currently organisms live static lifespans with fixed morphology. Introducing temporal phases allows evolution to discover that *delayed beauty* works—organisms can be utilitarian early and invest in aesthetics later. This breaks the zero-sum tradeoff between survival efficiency and beauty. Japanese aesthetics of transient beauty could emerge naturally.; [easy] Enforce fractal/self-similar growth patterns. Add growth rules that reward recursive branching (each branch spawns smaller branches of the same structure). Bonus fitness for patterns visible at 2+ scales. Organisms evolve to grow like trees, ferns, or lightning—structures that are inherently beautiful because they're fractal. — Natural beauty is often fractal. Most plateaus hit because evolution explores the space of random shapes exhaustively. By codifying fractality as a structural rule (not a parameter), you reduce the search space to *meaningful* shapes only. Evolution can then refine within that constraint rather than searching noise.",
